The typical way of doing this in JS/TS is to throw an `Error` (i.e. `reject(new Error(...))`).

If we want to include more information along with the error, we can extend `Error`, something like:

```typescript
export class CommandError extends Error {
    constructor(message: string, readonly result: CommandResult) {
        super(message)
        this.name = "CommandError"
    }
}
```

Users would then be able to catch and inspect the additional information in the error:

```typescript
try {
    const result = await runPulumiCmd(...);
} catch (err) {
    if (err instanceof CommandError) {
        // Use err.result...
        console.log(err.result.stderr);
    }
}
```

This is similar to how `axios` (an http client library) does it: https://github.com/axios/axios#handling-errors

Some more info: https://javascript.info/custom-errors

